, we propose SwiftAgg which reduces the server communication load via partitioning users into several groups and using Shamirâ€™s secret sharing [15] to keep the local models private. SwiftAgg is able to achieve correct aggregation in presence of up to Dğ·D dropout users, with formally-proven the worst-case security guarantee against up to Tğ‘‡T semi-honest users. Independently, similar ideas have been used in CodedSecAgg [16], but dropout users in groups have not been addressed and there is no formal definition and proof of privacy. The communication loads and the computation loads of the existing approaches are compared in TableÂ I.

TableÂ I compares different schemes for secure aggregation problem in terms of the communication and computation loads. For a fair comparison, we consider two metrics: the server communication load and the per-user communication load. Server communication load indicates the aggregated size of all messages which are sent or received by the server, and per-user communication load denotes the aggregated size of all messages which are sent by each user. Furthermore, server and per-user computations indicate the computation loads of the server and each user respectively. In this table, the computational complexity of the schemes in [12, 7, 14], and SwiftAgg+, is calculated based on Reed-Solomon decoding complexity [18]. Any improvements in this complexity can be applied to those schemes.
